            <p>Reading this magnificent text, one understands even more the urgency of a global research agenda on oceans and seas as an answer to the questions that assail us from the urgency of the environmental and climate crisis. It is a text of a high level of reflection, which allows us to understand the paths travelled for marine research, indicates the points to be completed in the future and provides us with reflections for the future. Scientific soundness, interdisciplinary dialogues and a systematisation of the work towards the future run through the pages of the article with enormous validity. Therefore, with this quality of research, my comments only make sense as proposals for dialogue and collaboration with the authors. They are only reflections born of the interesting elements that are proposed in the text, answers that I also seek in my own research.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Environmental historians, with a strong focus on land, agrarian and peasant historians, have much to learn from the challenges presented in this magnificent article.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <bold>Methodological Challenges.</bold>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In this first section I will express ideas and proposals arising from the methodological profiles proposed in the text.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <italic>Supporting a Non-Human-Centric Matrix</italic>
                <italic>.</italic>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The first of these stems from interdisciplinarity, which is present in the text in all its aspects, but which may have more possible tools. From the field of environmental history in which some of us move, the links with archaeology and history have been and are constants in our daily work. This dialogue is very much embedded in the narrative of the text but it would be good to reinforce the dialogues from Environmental History, the processes of historical co-evolution as opposed to social and environmental determinisms, making the historical processes from the Modern Age to the present more complex. To this end, the text invites us to continue with the History of Animals, of Non-Human Beings in our agenda, which many of us should implement in our research.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <italic>Contributions to a Non-Eurocentric Matrix and Communality</italic>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> A second challenge is the Eurocentric rupture of the text, a logical consequence of the projects that contribute to it. There are many research experiences that we have developed in many other oceans that are not coeval with the logics described in the text, nor do they have the same timelines (in our work in the Pacific Ocean, Baja California Sur, the transition from hunter-gatherers to ocean commodification occurred between 1700 and 1830), nor similar logics of appropriation of goods. We know about this proposal of the authors and it is described in a few paragraphs, but to understand even more about the Oceans we need to look very broadly at the Global South. We are developing projects on shark consumption in Reunion Island, or the difficulty around loggerhead turtle consumption or totoaba in Mexico are just some of the tasks we are engaged in in many places that can bring knowledge to this agenda.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Linked to this debate, the reflection on the Global Commons applied to marine and oceanic resources, pushes us to reflect on the forms of communality that have survived throughout history, parallel to the implementation of a "capitalisation of Nature" since the mid-18th century. This could be a very fertile field for pooling research on a global scale.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> This openness to research in non-European territories, which in many cases is carried out by researchers from European institutions in addition to our projects in Europe, could allow us to design a greater and better response to global challenges in socio-environmental research on the oceans, given the interaction between many of the processes of change in the management of natural assets.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> How can we create such common global agendas?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <italic>Contributions to a Quantitative Research Matrix</italic>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In addition to the above, the authors point out very well the limitations to go beyond the Baselines before 1950-60, following FAO statistics. It is true of the difficulty but we can collaborate between different disciplines to establish local projects in the oceans in order to - using the methodology of Material Energy Flow Accounts, MEFA - design local baselines with the use of historical material from archives and a central element, the memory of the inhabitants of the oceans, of the seas... the Biocultural Memory that allows the recovery of traditional knowledge and know-how of the coastal peoples.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> This assessment of territorial sustainability with a historical matrix can resolve this baseline limitation and provide valuable information with which to design a new communality as a social tool for the sustainability of the oceans and seas, with local knowledge.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> This can facilitate a methodological leap already mentioned, how to investigate, what archival materials we use, how we put into dialogue with tools of participatory and collaborative research, new research agendas in which archaeology, history and anthropology can give other possible results. This proposal may require "decolonising research processes", especially outside European contexts.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Can we design platforms of biophysical, social and emotional indicators, from interdisciplinary contributions, for the design of future sustainability tools and provide input to EU public policies?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <bold>Proposals for new dialogues.</bold>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> This magnificent text provides insights to new fields of research in the future, which emerge from the many already indicated in it and from some that are pointed out in it, and we can cite some ideas for the future.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <italic>Production</italic>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Oceans are (fluid) territories with intense levels of disputes, of environmental conflicts arising from the well-described process of commodification of natural resources (Anthropocene vs. Capitalocene?). This view of the oceans as resource providers, subject to intense extraction processes, should not make us forget that they are avenues for the implementation of new forms of commodification in the Global South: Guano, salt, raw materials, mother-of-pearl and pearls, turtles, underwater mining... are just some of the examples of this old-new intensive exploitation of the seas as such and as "highways for great acceleration".&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <italic>Consumption</italic>
            </p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> If we can build historical baselines, pre 60's, it will be easy to establish laboratories in many ocean territories on changes in agri-food systems, changes in diets, changes in human consumption patterns on marine goods. This change in food systems must be connected to changes in agrarian patterns (working with MEFA tools may be easier to assess quantitatively and qualitatively) since for many peoples the agrarian and the marine are integral to consumption patterns.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Inequalities in consumption levels, the need for a new form of relationship and access to marine goods in the face of ecocide may allow for a new Political Ecology of the Oceans to be generated in which to integrate both social and environmental inequity and the socio-environmental tensions that occur around material hexaction.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Finally, congratulations to the text for the work, which is enormous and of the highest quality. But above all, congratulations for inviting us to think about our research proposals and to incorporate many of these proposals into projects. I am sure that many dialogues will arise in the future to share.</p>
            <p>Is the argument persuasive and supported by appropriate evidence?</p>
            <p>Yes</p>
            <p>Is the work clearly and cogently presented?</p>
            <p>Yes</p>
            <p>Is the topic of the essay discussed accurately in the context of the current literature?</p>
            <p>Yes</p>
            <p>Does the essay contribute to the cultural, historical, social understanding of the field?</p>
            <p>Yes</p>
            <p>Reviewer Expertise:</p>
            <p>Environmental History, Environmental Conflicts, Ocean History</p>
            <p>I confirm that I have read this submission and believe that I have an appropriate level of expertise to confirm that it is of an acceptable scientific standard.</p>
